{
  "answer": "**In the Āṅgirasa Smṛti**, *saṃskāras* (translated here as \"sacraments\") are likened to colors that gradually reveal a painting, such that Brahminhood itself emerges through their cumulative application with mantras: \"Just as a painting is slowly revealed by many colors, so too is Brahminhood by sacraments preceded by mantras.\"[^1]\n\nEnglish terms like \"rite\" (emphasizing ceremony) or \"sacrament\" (suggesting consecration) lose *saṃskāra*'s core sense of an impression or purification (*sam* + √kṛ, \"to make perfect\")—the indelible inner mark that the rite etches on the person, refining and manifesting their spiritual essence over time.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-4891e8).\n[^2]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-3b5116).",
